So `ResponseError` only has two public properties: `Code` and `Message`. The deserialization works through the converter, which constructs the object from JSON.

Now I need to decide on my approach:For **serialization** of `ResponseError`:- The converter's `Write` throws `NotImplementedException`- So the only way to serialize is to manually write the JSON properties- Since `ResponseError` only has `Code` and `Message` public properties, I can write:```csharp
writer.WriteStartObject();
if (Error.Code != null)
{
    writer.WritePropertyName("code"u8);


```

Writing serialization logic...

For **deserialization** of `ResponseError`:- The converter's `Read` works fine- I need an AOT-safe way to call it- Since we verified the converter can be instantiated, we can create a static `JsonSerializerOptions` with it pre-registered- But this requires `Activator.CreateInstance` which has its own trim issues...

Actually, I should reconsider this approach entirely.
```

The real issue is that `JsonSerializer` discovers the converter through reflection via the `[JsonConverter]` attribute, which doesn't work with AOT. But if I pre-register the converter in `JsonSerializerOptions`, I skip that discovery step entirely. Since the internal `Azure.ResponseError+Converter` can be instantiated and the source generator can't see it anyway, I could either wrap it in a custom converter or just pre-create the options with it registered. The cleanest path forward is probably writing a custom `ResponseErrorConverter` that manually deserializes the JSON and constructs the object, then handling serialization similarly.

```

csharp
internal class ResponseErrorConverter : JsonConverter<ResponseError>
{
    private static readonly JsonConverter<ResponseError> s_inner = 
        (JsonConverter<ResponseError>)Activator.CreateInstance(
            typeof(ResponseError).GetCustomAttribute<JsonConverterAttribute>()!.ConverterType, 
            nonPublic: true)!;

    public override ResponseError Read(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, Type typeToConvert, JsonSerializerOptions options)
        => s_inner.Read(ref reader, typeToConvert, options);

    public override void Write(Utf8JsonWriter writer, ResponseError value, JsonSerializerOptions options)
    {
        writer.WriteStartObject();
        if (value.Code != null)
        {
            writer.WritePropertyName("code"u8);
            writer.WriteStringValue(value.Code);
        }
        if (value.Message != null)
        {
            writer.WritePropertyName("message"u8);
            writer.WriteStringValue(value.Message);
        }
        writer.WriteEndObject();
    }
}
```

Building the wrapper converter... Still writing converter... I'm reconsidering the approach here—while a simplified converter that only reads `code` and `message` would work for AOT, it would lose internal fields like `target`, `details`, and `innererror` during round-tripping. The original Azure.Core converter preserves all this data even if it's not exposed publicly, so I need to write a converter that captures all known fields using the full constructor signature to maintain data integrity. Writing the serializer methods...

The issue is that `ResponseError` doesn't implement `IJsonModel<ResponseError>`, so calling `WriteObjectValue` will fail. I need to use `JsonSerializer.Serialize` with the proper context instead. I'll delete and recreate the serializer context, add a custom converter for `ResponseError`, and fix both the serialization and deserialization calls to use the correct approach.

